# Preventing Unnecessary Re-renders in React

When a parent component re-renders, **all child components re-render by default**, regardless of whether their props changed. Here are the solutions:

---

## 1. `React.memo` (Function Components)

Wraps your component to skip re-renders when props are **shallowly equal**:

```jsx
// ❌ Before: Re-renders every time parent updates
const ExpensiveList = ({ items, onSelect }) => {
  console.log('Rendering ExpensiveList'); // fires on every parent render
  return (
    <ul>
      {items.map(item => (
        <li key={item.id} onClick={() => onSelect(item.id)}>
          {item.name}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
};

// ✅ After: Only re-renders when `items` or `onSelect` actually change
const ExpensiveList = React.memo(({ items, onSelect }) => {
  console.log('Rendering ExpensiveList'); // only fires when props change
  return (
    <ul>
      {items.map(item => (
        <li key={item.id} onClick={() => onSelect(item.id)}>
          {item.name}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
});
```

### Custom comparison (for deep equality):

```jsx
const ExpensiveList = React.memo(MyComponent, (prevProps, nextProps) => {
  // Return true to SKIP re-render, false to re-render
  return prevProps.items.length === nextProps.items.length &&
         prevProps.items.every((item, i) => item.id === nextProps.items[i].id);
});
```

---

## 2. Fix the Root Cause: Unstable Props

`React.memo` **won't help** if you're passing new references every render:

```jsx
const Parent = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // ❌ New function reference every render — defeats React.memo
  const handleSelect = (id) => console.log(id);

  // ❌ New array reference every render — defeats React.memo
  const items = [{ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }];

  // ❌ New object reference every render — defeats React.memo
  const style = { color: 'red' };

  return <ExpensiveList items={items} onSelect={handleSelect} style={style} />;
};
```

### ✅ Fix with `useCallback` and `useMemo`:

```jsx
const Parent = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const [items, setItems] = useState([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }]);

  // ✅ Stable function reference
  const handleSelect = useCallback((id) => {
    console.log(id);
  }, []); // empty deps = same reference across renders

  // ✅ Stable object reference (recomputed only when deps change)
  const style = useMemo(() => ({ color: 'red' }), []);

  // ✅ items is already in state, so reference is stable unless setItems is called

  return <ExpensiveList items={items} onSelect={handleSelect} style={style} />;
};
```

---

## 3. Quick Reference: Which Hook Solves What

```
Problem                          Solution
─────────────────────────────    ──────────────
Child re-renders unnecessarily   React.memo()
Callback prop changes each       useCallback()
render
Computed/object prop changes     useMemo()
each render
```

---

## 4. Visual Summary of How It Works

```
Parent re-renders
       │
       ▼
  Props changed?  ──── React.memo comparison
       │                     │
      Yes                   No
       │                     │
       ▼                     ▼
  Child renders        Child SKIPS render ✅
```

---

## ⚠️ Common Pitfalls

| Mistake | Why It Fails |
|---|---|
| Inline objects/arrays as props | New reference every render |
| Inline arrow functions as props | New reference every render |
| Spreading `{...props}` unnecessarily | May include changing refs |
| Missing `useCallback` dependencies | Stale closures / bugs |
| Memoizing **everything** | Adds overhead — only memoize expensive components |

> **Rule of thumb:** Don't optimize prematurely. Use React DevTools **Profiler** to identify *actual* slow re-renders first, then apply `React.memo` + `useCallback`/`useMemo` selectively.

# Document Analysis Pipeline — Recommended Architecture

Here's a practical architecture that balances capability with simplicity.

## High-Level Flow

```
PDF Upload → Extract & Chunk → Analyze Chunks → Cross-Reference → Structured Summary
```

## Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Orchestrator                          │
│              (Python script / simple server)             │
└──────┬──────────┬──────────────┬───────────────┬────────┘
       │          │              │               │
       ▼          ▼              ▼               ▼
   ┌────────┐ ┌────────────┐ ┌────────────┐ ┌──────────┐
   │ Files  │ │  Haiku 4.5 │ │ Sonnet 4.5 │ │  Batch   │
   │  API   │ │  Chunked   │ │  Synthesis  │ │   API    │
   │        │ │ Extraction │ │  & Summary  │ │ (if async│
   │(upload │ │            │ │            │ │  is OK)  │
   │ once)  │ │ (per-chunk)│ │(final pass)│ │  50% off │
   └────────┘ └────────────┘ └────────────┘ └──────────┘
```

## Step-by-Step Design

### 1. Upload & Cache the PDF (Files API)

Upload once, reference many times — no re-uploading per request.

